<!--
	ws-line-integrals.ptx
	Section 2 (Line Integrals and Green's Theorem), worksheet 8:
	Line Integrals.

	Ported from the Beamer deck 02_01_LineIntegrals.tex (in
	outdated-material/notes/, line-integrals folder): scalar line
	integrals, vector line integrals, work, and the mass of a wire.
	Book concepts tracked from sec_line_int_intro (scalar fields, mass)
	and sec_line_int_vf (vector fields, work); the Fundamental Theorem of
	Line Integrals / conservative fields are deferred to worksheet 10
	(ws-path-independence). Example equations are NOT reused from the deck
	or the book.

	Authored to the SHARED worksheet conventions
	(checklists/worksheet-conventions.md): paired component="stu"/"key"
	reading checks and exercises; one True/False misconception check; one
	read-along TikZ figure; one modern application. Standard notation
	(macros from source/notes/bookends/docinfo.ptx); no new macros.
	Math-valued answer keys are underlined directly (\underline{...});
	only plain-word answers are bolded, so the pdf-key (LaTeX) build stays
	clean.
-->
<worksheet xml:id="ws-line-integrals">
	<title>Line Integrals</title>

	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li>Evaluate a scalar line integral <m>\int_C f\,ds</m> by parametrizing <m>C</m> and replacing <m>ds</m> with <m>\norm{\vr'(t)}\,dt</m>.</li>
			<li>Evaluate a vector line integral <m>\int_C \vF\cdot d\vr = \int_a^b \vF(\vr(t))\cdot\vr'(t)\,dt</m>.</li>
			<li>Interpret <m>\int_C \vF\cdot d\vr</m> as the work done by a force field along a path.</li>
			<li>Use orientation and linearity to relate line integrals over related paths.</li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 1: Scalar line integrals
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>I. The line integral of a scalar function.</term></p>

		<p>
			An ordinary integral sums a function over an interval of the
			<m>x</m>-axis. A <term>line integral</term> instead sums a
			function over a <em>curve</em> <m>C</m>. If <m>C</m> is
			parametrized by <m>\vr(t)</m> for <m>a\le t\le b</m>, we weight
			each value of <m>f</m> by the arclength element
			<m>ds = \norm{\vr'(t)}\,dt</m> and integrate:
			<md>
				\int_C f\,ds = \int_a^b f\big(\vr(t)\big)\,\norm{\vr'(t)}\,dt .
			</md>
			The factor <m>\norm{\vr'(t)}</m> (the speed) converts a step
			<m>dt</m> in the parameter into the true distance <m>ds</m>
			traveled along the curve.
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 1 -->
		<p component="stu">
			A line integral sums a function over a
			<fillin characters="5"/> <nbsp/>rather than an interval. To
			evaluate <m>\int_C f\,ds</m> we replace the arclength element by
			<m>ds = </m> <fillin characters="10"/> <m>\,dt</m>.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			A line integral sums a function over a
			<m>\underline{\textbf{curve}}</m> rather than an interval. To
			evaluate <m>\int_C f\,ds</m> we replace the arclength element by
			<m>ds = \underline{\norm{\vr'(t)}}\,dt</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Evaluate <m>\int_C f\,ds</m> for <m>f(x,y) = 2x</m>, where
					<m>C</m> is the straight segment from <m>(0,0)</m> to
					<m>(3,4)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Evaluate <m>\int_C f\,ds</m> for <m>f(x,y) = 2x</m>, where
					<m>C</m> is the straight segment from <m>(0,0)</m> to
					<m>(3,4)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Parametrize the segment as
					<m>\vr(t) = [\,3t,\; 4t\,]</m>, <m>t\in[0,1]</m>. Then
					<m>\vr'(t) = [\,3,\,4\,]</m> and
					<m>\norm{\vr'(t)} = \sqrt{3^2+4^2} = 5</m>. Along the curve
					<m>f = 2x = 2(3t) = 6t</m>, so
					<md>
						\int_C f\,ds = \int_0^1 (6t)(5)\,dt
						= 30\int_0^1 t\,dt = 30\cdot\tfrac12 = 15 .
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p><term>Your turn.</term></p>

		<!-- practice problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Evaluate <m>\int_C f\,ds</m> for <m>f(x,y) = x - y</m>,
					where <m>C</m> is the straight segment from <m>(1,0)</m> to
					<m>(4,4)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Evaluate <m>\int_C f\,ds</m> for <m>f(x,y) = x - y</m>,
					where <m>C</m> is the straight segment from <m>(1,0)</m> to
					<m>(4,4)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					A parametrization is
					<m>\vr(t) = [\,1+3t,\; 4t\,]</m>, <m>t\in[0,1]</m>, with
					<m>\vr'(t) = [\,3,\,4\,]</m> and <m>\norm{\vr'(t)} = 5</m>.
					Along <m>C</m>, <m>f = x - y = (1+3t) - 4t = 1 - t</m>, so
					<md>
						\int_C f\,ds = \int_0^1 (1-t)(5)\,dt
						= 5\left(1 - \tfrac12\right) = \tfrac{5}{2} .
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 2: Vector line integrals and work
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>II. The line integral of a vector field.</term></p>

		<p>
			To integrate a <em>vector field</em> <m>\vF</m> along <m>C</m> we
			add up the component of <m>\vF</m> <em>along</em> the curve. With
			<m>d\vr = \vr'(t)\,dt</m>,
			<md>
				\int_C \vF\cdot d\vr
				= \int_a^b \vF\big(\vr(t)\big)\cdot\vr'(t)\,dt .
			</md>
			The dot product picks out how much of the field points the way we
			are traveling. When <m>\vF</m> is a <term>force</term>, this line
			integral is exactly the <term>work</term> done on a particle
			moving along <m>C</m> <ndash/> a running total of
			<m>(\text{force})\cdot(\text{small displacement})</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- reading-check pair 2 -->
		<p component="stu">
			The vector line integral is <m>\int_C \vF\cdot d\vr = \int_a^b</m>
			<fillin characters="8"/> <m>\cdot</m> <fillin characters="6"/>
			<m>\,dt</m>. When <m>\vF</m> is a force field, this integral
			computes the <fillin characters="5"/> <nbsp/>done along <m>C</m>.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			The vector line integral is
			<m>\int_C \vF\cdot d\vr = \int_a^b \underline{\vF(\vr(t))} \cdot
			\underline{\vr'(t)}\,dt</m>. When <m>\vF</m> is a force field,
			this integral computes the <m>\underline{\textbf{work}}</m> done
			along <m>C</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Evaluate <m>\int_C \vF\cdot d\vr</m> for
					<m>\vF = [\,xy,\; y\,]</m>, where <m>C</m> is the arc of the
					parabola <m>y = x^2</m> from <m>(0,0)</m> to <m>(2,4)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Evaluate <m>\int_C \vF\cdot d\vr</m> for
					<m>\vF = [\,xy,\; y\,]</m>, where <m>C</m> is the arc of the
					parabola <m>y = x^2</m> from <m>(0,0)</m> to <m>(2,4)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Let <m>x = t</m>, so <m>\vr(t) = [\,t,\; t^2\,]</m> for
					<m>t\in[0,2]</m> and <m>\vr'(t) = [\,1,\; 2t\,]</m>. Along
					<m>C</m>,
					<m>\vF = [\,xy,\,y\,] = [\,t\cdot t^2,\; t^2\,] = [\,t^3,\,t^2\,]</m>,
					so
					<md>
						\vF(\vr(t))\cdot\vr'(t)
						= [\,t^3,\,t^2\,]\cdot[\,1,\,2t\,]
						= t^3 + 2t^3 = 3t^3 .
					</md>
					Therefore
					<md>
						\int_C \vF\cdot d\vr = \int_0^2 3t^3\,dt
						= \left. \tfrac{3}{4}t^4 \right|_0^2 = \tfrac34(16) = 12 .
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 3: Work in a force field; orientation and linearity
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>III. Work, orientation, and linearity.</term></p>

		<p>
			Two properties make line integrals easier to handle. They are
			<term>linear</term>,
			<m>\int_C (\vF+\vG)\cdot d\vr = \int_C \vF\cdot d\vr
			+ \int_C \vG\cdot d\vr</m>, and they respond to
			<term>orientation</term>: traversing <m>C</m> backwards (call it
			<m>-C</m>) reverses every <m>d\vr</m>, so
			<m>\int_{-C}\vF\cdot d\vr = -\int_C \vF\cdot d\vr</m>. (A scalar
			integral <m>\int_C f\,ds</m> does <em>not</em> flip <ndash/>
			length <m>ds</m> is always positive.)
		</p>

		<figure xml:id="ws-lineint-fig-work">
			<caption>Work along a path: at each point the force
				<m>\vF</m> is dotted with the small displacement
				<m>d\vr</m> tangent to <m>C</m>. Here <m>\vF = [\,-y,\,x\,]</m>,
				the rotational field from the last worksheet, pushes along the
				quarter circle the whole way.</caption>
			<image width="52%">
				<shortdescription>A quarter-circle arc in the first quadrant from the point (1,0) to (0,1); at a sample point on the arc a force arrow is drawn tangent to the circle, alongside a short displacement arrow in the same direction.</shortdescription>
				<latex-image>
	\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=2.2,>=stealth]
	% axes
	\draw[->] (-0.15,0) -- (1.4,0) node[anchor=north] {$x$};
	\draw[->] (0,-0.15) -- (0,1.4) node[anchor=east] {$y$};
	% quarter circle from (1,0) to (0,1)
	\draw[very thick, blue] (1,0) arc (0:90:1);
	\node[blue] at (0.86,0.86) {$C$};
	% endpoints
	\fill (1,0) circle (0.5pt) node[anchor=north] {$(1,0)$};
	\fill (0,1) circle (0.5pt) node[anchor=east] {$(0,1)$};
	% sample point at t = pi/4: (cos45, sin45)
	\coordinate (P) at (0.7071,0.7071);
	\fill (P) circle (0.7pt);
	% force F = [-y, x] at P = [-0.7071, 0.7071], tangent, counterclockwise.
	% Explicit endpoints (no calc library): P + (-0.35, 0.35) and P + (-0.18, 0.18).
	\draw[very thick, red, ->] (0.7071,0.7071) -- (0.3571,1.0571);
	\node[red, anchor=west] at (0.5,1.18) {$\vF$};
	% small displacement dr, same direction, shorter
	\draw[very thick, teal, ->] (0.7071,0.7071) -- (0.5271,0.8871);
	\node[teal, anchor=north west] at (0.62,0.66) {$d\vr$};
	\end{tikzpicture}
				</latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>

		<!-- reading-check pair 3 -->
		<p component="stu">
			Line integrals are <fillin characters="6"/>, so a field that
			splits as <m>\vF+\vG</m> can be integrated piece by piece.
			Reversing the orientation of <m>C</m> <fillin characters="5"/>
			<nbsp/>the sign of <m>\int_C \vF\cdot d\vr</m>.
		</p>
		<p component="key">
			Line integrals are <m>\underline{\textbf{linear}}</m>, so a field
			that splits as <m>\vF+\vG</m> can be integrated piece by piece.
			Reversing the orientation of <m>C</m>
			<m>\underline{\textbf{flips}}</m> the sign of
			<m>\int_C \vF\cdot d\vr</m>.
		</p>

		<!-- worked problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the work done by the rotational force field
					<m>\vF = [\,-y,\; x\,]</m> on a particle moving along the
					quarter circle of radius <m>1</m> from <m>(1,0)</m> to
					<m>(0,1)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the work done by the rotational force field
					<m>\vF = [\,-y,\; x\,]</m> on a particle moving along the
					quarter circle of radius <m>1</m> from <m>(1,0)</m> to
					<m>(0,1)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Parametrize the arc as
					<m>\vr(t) = [\,\cos t,\; \sin t\,]</m>,
					<m>t\in[0,\tfrac{\pi}{2}]</m>, so
					<m>\vr'(t) = [\,-\sin t,\; \cos t\,]</m>. Along <m>C</m>,
					<m>\vF = [\,-y,\,x\,] = [\,-\sin t,\; \cos t\,]</m>, hence
					<md>
						\vF(\vr(t))\cdot\vr'(t)
						= (-\sin t)(-\sin t) + (\cos t)(\cos t)
						= \sin^2 t + \cos^2 t = 1 .
					</md>
					The field points along the path the entire way, so
					<md>
						W = \int_C \vF\cdot d\vr = \int_0^{\pi/2} 1\,dt
						= \tfrac{\pi}{2} .
					</md>
					(Traversing the arc the other way, from <m>(0,1)</m> to
					<m>(1,0)</m>, would give <m>-\tfrac{\pi}{2}</m>.)
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p><term>Your turn.</term></p>

		<!-- practice problem (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the work done by <m>\vF = [\,2x,\; x+y\,]</m> along the
					straight segment from <m>(0,0)</m> to <m>(1,3)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					Find the work done by <m>\vF = [\,2x,\; x+y\,]</m> along the
					straight segment from <m>(0,0)</m> to <m>(1,3)</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Take <m>\vr(t) = [\,t,\; 3t\,]</m>, <m>t\in[0,1]</m>, with
					<m>\vr'(t) = [\,1,\,3\,]</m>. Along <m>C</m>,
					<m>\vF = [\,2t,\; t+3t\,] = [\,2t,\,4t\,]</m>, so
					<m>\vF\cdot\vr' = 2t + 12t = 14t</m> and
					<md>
						W = \int_0^1 14t\,dt = 7 .
					</md>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>
	</page>

	<!-- ============================================================
		 Page 4: A misconception, an application, and looking ahead
		 ============================================================ -->
	<page>
		<p><term>IV. A caution and an application.</term></p>

		<!-- misconception check: single exercise, solution instructor-only -->
		<exercise xml:id="ws-lineint-tf-orientation">
			<statement>
				<p>
					<alert>True or False.</alert> Reversing the direction in
					which a particle travels along <m>C</m> leaves the value of
					<m>\int_C \vF\cdot d\vr</m> unchanged. Explain, and say what
					happens to <m>\int_C f\,ds</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution component="key">
				<p>
					<term>False</term> for the vector line integral. Reversing
					the orientation reverses every displacement <m>d\vr</m>, so
					<m>\int_{-C}\vF\cdot d\vr = -\int_C \vF\cdot d\vr</m>: the
					work changes sign (pushing a box east then dragging it back
					west undoes the work). The <em>scalar</em> line integral
					<m>\int_C f\,ds</m> is unchanged, because <m>ds</m> is a
					positive length element that does not care which way we
					walk. Orientation matters for <m>d\vr</m>, not for
					<m>ds</m>.
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<p><term>An application.</term></p>

		<!-- application (paired) -->
		<exercise component="stu" workspace="2.5in">
			<statement>
				<p>
					A thin wire is bent into the upper half of the unit circle,
					from <m>(1,0)</m> to <m>(-1,0)</m>. Its linear density at a
					point is <m>\delta(x,y) = y</m> (denser near the top). Find
					the mass of the wire, <m>m = \int_C \delta\,ds</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</exercise>
		<exercise component="key">
			<statement>
				<p>
					A thin wire is bent into the upper half of the unit circle,
					from <m>(1,0)</m> to <m>(-1,0)</m>. Its linear density at a
					point is <m>\delta(x,y) = y</m> (denser near the top). Find
					the mass of the wire, <m>m = \int_C \delta\,ds</m>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			<solution>
				<p>
					Parametrize the upper semicircle by
					<m>\vr(t) = [\,\cos t,\; \sin t\,]</m>,
					<m>t\in[0,\pi]</m>, so
					<m>\norm{\vr'(t)} = 1</m> and <m>ds = dt</m>. Along the
					wire <m>\delta = y = \sin t</m>, so
					<md>
						m = \int_C \delta\,ds = \int_0^{\pi} \sin t\,dt
						= \big[-\cos t\big]_0^{\pi}
						= 1 - (-1) = 2 .
					</md>
					The mass is heavier toward the top, exactly where the
					density is largest. (A uniform wire of the same length
					<m>\pi</m> would instead have mass <m>\pi</m> if
					<m>\delta = 1</m>.)
				</p>
			</solution>
		</exercise>

		<conclusion>
			<p>
				<alert>Looking ahead.</alert> We can now integrate along a
				curve <ndash/> length-weighted totals with <m>ds</m>, and work
				and circulation with <m>d\vr</m>. Next we return to the
				<term>divergence</term> and <term>curl</term> of a field and
				connect them to these integrals: <term>Green's Theorem</term>
				will equate the circulation of a field around a closed loop
				with the total curl swept out over the region inside it,
				turning a line integral into a double integral.
			</p>
		</conclusion>
	</page>

</worksheet>
